journals, American Scream shows how Howl brought Ginsberg and the world out of the closet of a repressive society. It also gives the first full accounting of the literary figures—Eliot, Rimbaud, and Whitman—who influenced Howl, definitively placing it in the tradition of twentieth-century American poetry for the first time. As he follows the genesis and the evolution of Howl, Jonah Raskin constructs a vivid picture of a poet and an era. He illuminates the development of Beat poetry in New York and San Francisco in the 1950s--focusing on historic occasions such as the first reading of Howl at Six Gallery in San Francisco in 1955 and the obscenity trial over the poem's publication. He looks closely at Ginsberg's life, including his relationships with his parents, friends, and mentors, while he was writing the poem and uses this material to illuminate the themes of madness, nakedness, and secrecy that pervade Howl.A captivating look at the cultural climate of the Cold War and at a great American poet, American Scream finally tells the full story of Howl—a rousing manifesto for a generation and a classic of twentieth-century literature.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aBeat generation. 0aBeats (Persons) 0aBeats (Persons). 0aLiterature and mental illnesszUnited StatesxHistoryy20th century. 0aMental illness in literature. 0aPoetryxPsychological aspects. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / American / General.2bisacsh  a20th century.  aallen ginsberg.  aamerica.  aamerican culture.  aamerican poetry.  aamerican poets.  aamerican society.  aart and literature.  abeat generation.  abeat movement.  abeat poets.  acold war america.  acontroversial.  acritical analysis.  acultural history.  ahistorical review.  ahowl.  ajack kerouac.  alit scholars.  alit studies.  aliterary criticism.  